{{Infobox person |name = Ildebrando Zacchini |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_name = |birth_date = 1868 |birth_place = [[Malta]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|1948|07|17|1868}} |death_place = [[Tampa, Florida]] |death_cause = |resting_place = [[Myrtle Hill Memorial Park]], Tampa |resting_place_coordinates = |residence = |nationality = [[Malta|Maltese]] |ethnicity = |citizenship = |other_names = |known_for = [[human cannonball]] act |education = |alma_mater = |employer = |occupation = |home_town = |title = |salary = |networth = |height = |weight = |term = |predecessor = |successor = |party = |boards = |religion = |spouse = Madelina Dal Paos (1872 &ndash; 1963) |partner = |children = [[Hugo Zacchini]], Edmondo Zacchini |parents = |relations = |callsign = |signature = |website = |footnotes = }} '''Ildebrando Zacchini''' (1868 - July 17, 1948, [[Tampa, Florida]]) was a [[Malta|Maltese]]-born [[painter]], [[inventor]], and [[travelling circus]] owner.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/obituaries/article1089283.ece?nsm=true|title=Rene Zacchini left circus to serve in Florida House...|date=April 22, 2010|publisher=''[[St. Petersburg Times]]''|accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref>
Inspired by the works of [[Jules Verne]], Zacchini came up with an idea for a [[human cannonball]] act.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HxoMAAAAIBAJ&sjid=TV0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6030,5671666&dq=ildebrando-zacchini&hl=en|title=Zacchini Cannon Enters Museum |date=March 31, 1976|publisher=''[[St. Petersburg Times]]''|accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref> Instead of explosives, Zacchini's human-firing cannon used compressed air, and he first tested it on his son [[Hugo Zacchini]].
The idea for the cannonball act was initially proposed to the Italian government as a military maneuver to be used in conjunction with [[parachute]]s; when the proposal was rejected Zacchini looked to use the technique as part of an entertainment act.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QPccAAAAIBAJ&sjid=p3sEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5725,287006&dq=ildebrando-zacchini&hl=en|title='Trigger man' behind human cannonball dies|date=January 11, 1993|publisher=''[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]''|accessdate=April 23, 2010}}</ref>
Members of the Zacchini family were later inducted into the [[Ringling Brothers]] Circus Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/8251137|title=Ildebrando Zacchini| publisher= Find A Grave|accessdate=August 14, 2012}}</ref>
